title: Installation, Free Universal Construction Kit, 2012
provenance: Acquired by  Cooper Hewitt directly from the printer, 2015.
dimensions:
H x W x D (largest connector): 10.8 x 9.8 x 8.6 cm (4 1/4 x 3 7/8 x 3 3/8 in.)
All remaining connectors are under 7.6 x 7.6 x 7.6 cm (3 in. x 3in. x 3 in.)
Sample object made with kit: 12.7 x 12.7 x 12.7 cm (5 in. x 5 in. x 5 in.)
creditline: Courtesy of F.A.T. Lab and Sy-Lab
description: Up to 80 small 3D-printed connectors. Produce 3D prints of components; combine with existing toy parts in an intriguing structure.
gallery_text: The Free Universal Construction Kit consists of nearly 80 adapter bricks connecting 10 popular construction toys. Users can download the files from various sharing sites and print them on a Makerbot or other personal 3D printer. The Kit demonstrates that reverse engineering is “a creative process in which anyone can develop the necessary pieces to bridge the limitations presented by mass-produced commercial artifacts.”
